Overview

This lab demonstrates how to enumerate an Active Directory environment, discover credentials, and escalate privileges to achieve full domain compromise.

Attack Path Summary
1. Initial Enumeration
Scanned the target to identify open ports and services
Confirmed the system was a Domain Controller
Identified:
Domain: academy.local
Hostname: DC200

2. SMB Enumeration (Guest Access)
Connected using the Guest account
Enumerated available SMB shares
Identified shares with read access:
Logs
Public

3. User Discovery
Accessed a readable share and found a file containing employee names
Extracted valid usernames from the file

4. Password Attack
Performed password spraying using a common password list
Successfully obtained credentials for:
dwhitmore

5. Active Directory Enumeration
Queried Active Directory users
Discovered a default password stored in a user description:
nholloway

6. Credential Validation
Verified the credentials worked against the target system

7. SYSVOL Enumeration
Investigated the SYSVOL share for misconfigurations
Found a Group Policy Preferences (GPP) file containing encrypted credentials

8. Exploiting GPP Vulnerability
Extracted and decrypted the stored password
Recovered credentials for:
stacy (privileged user)

9. Privilege Escalation
Used the new credentials to gain administrative access on the Domain Controller

10. Credential Dumping
Deployed Mimikatz on the Domain Controller
Dumped credentials from memory / SAM database

11. Full Compromise
Retrieved the NTLM hash of the Domain Administrator account
Achieved full domain compromise

Key Takeaways
Misconfigured SMB shares can expose sensitive data
Weak and reused passwords are easily exploitable
Active Directory attributes (like descriptions) may leak credentials
SYSVOL is a high-value target for attackers
GPP passwords are insecure and reversible
Credential chaining leads to full domain compromise
